/r9k/ is an imageboard where there are no exact reposts.

1. If you attempt to post something unoriginal, it is not posted, and you are muted temporarily.
2. The time with which you are muted for doubles with each transgression.
3. Each mute time is 2^n in seconds where n is the number of times you have transgressed. So, your mute time doubles each time you fuck up.
4. Backlinks, eg >>1, are not viewed by the robot. So "lolwut" and ">>2 lolwut" are the same post, in the eyes of the robot.
5. Gibberish at the end of a post to force originality may result in mod intervention (no BLOX posts please).
6. Images are NOT included in the filter, only text.
7. Your mute count slowly decreases over time.
8. You cannot post a picture without text.
9. Unicode is blocked. Sorry, too many exploits (Cyrillic letters, etc).
10. Posts require a certain minimum amount of original content in order to be posted.
11. Post sane, real content, well thought out replies, and mutes are unlikely.
12. The original algorithm was designed by XKCD:
http://blag.xkcd.com/2008/01/14/robot9000-and-xkcd-signal-attacking-noise-in-chat/

Sure, I'll have another dinosaur fact after this post. This one is paleontology related though, so you may still enjoy it.

Pic related is of an ancient fungus. Its not entirely clear as to what it entirely was, but it reigned on land before vascular plants(any plant that isn't a moss or liverwort and thus can be tall) loomed and made whole forests. Prototaxites was originally mistaken to be a type of yew, thus their taxonomic name which means "first yew." However, the microstructure of the fossils revealed that it was nothing quite like a plant but instead a type of fungus. It's not entirely clear if prototaxites utilized photosynthesis, as there are microfossils showing what appear to be algae within its cells, and additionally prototaxites are theorized to be most closely related to lichens who are photosynthetic due to their algae symbionts. However, isotope analyses on prototaxites shows that they seemed to be primarily, if not exclusively, heterotrophic.

posts.com: The Theropod dinosaurs, the group which contained not only the largest land animals to ever exist, but also the largest land predators and the likes of T. Rex, owe their size to their unique weight-reduction adaptations(which also had other functions). Theropods, and thus sauropods and birds by extension, utilize and utilized a system of air sacs along their spine that helped to reduce their density. Their respiratory systems were also more efficient and capable than those of mammals, which was almost certainly part of why they were and are so successful today.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com: Te (extraverted thinking) isn't required to achieve productivity and success because if this were true, then only TJs would be successful in life but we know this isn't the case. It's more that Te makes it easier for us to be productive and to act because it naturally minimizes complexity and maximizes simplicity. Too much nuance and too many exemptions inflate tasks/goals/actions out of proportion, they make things dizzying and unmanageable which ultimately results in procrastination, demoralization, and/or inaction. If you want to see an example of spiraling overcomplication, talk to your resident NP and try to organize anything with them. We achieve this simplification by collecting external data, analyzing generalized assumptions ("facts"), creating estimations (generally correct but never perfect), and building systems of standardization by chaining everything together. This is its core strength and a critical one because action is driven by simplicity and blocked by complexity.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Think of clothing sizes for a moment- why do clothing sizes like XS, S, M, L, XL exist? Why don't fashion companies take the time to individually make custom pieces of clothing for every single human being with different body proportions on the planet? The answer is that it's extremely time and energy intensive to make bespoke pieces of clothing whether by hand or by machine. It would also be crazy expensive. The solution then is to make standardized clothing sizes based on generalized assumptions of "normal" human proportions. The thought of having to measure every single person on the planet and sew custom pieces of clothing for every unique and nuanced body type is overwhelming, but simplifying it down to 5 standardized sizes (XS, S, M, L, XL) is not because it's actionable. Simplicity unlocks action.

Now think of job hunting- why do job applications exist? Why don't employers take the time to individually talk to every single person who applies to a position? The answer is that it's extremely time and energy intensive to speak to every single person and personally verify they're qualified. It's also expensive. The solution then is to rely on signals like grades, university, test scores, and past employment based on generalized assumptions of competence, ability, and intelligence. The thought of spending weeks and months interviewing every single candidate to vet their abilities is overwhelming, but simplifying it down to 5-10 candidates based on signals is not because it's actionable. Simplicity unlocks action.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Imagine having to host a dinner party for 100 people where every single person's unique and different food preferences had to be accommodated- you'd never be able to start cooking, or, you'd have to cook 100 different dishes. A set menu (essentially a culinary generalization) is easier to manage. Everyone won't get exactly what they want but most people will, it simplifies the problem, and it's actionable. Simplicity unlocks action.

Complexity accounts for many details and nuances which makes it more precise, but it's also very expensive in time/money/energy, very slow, and results in lower productivity. Simplicity streamlines assumptions, removes confusion, and accelerates productivity, but it can be seen as "brutish" and imprecise because it minimizes nuance/individualism (a main complaint from FPs). Te takes large and complex problems by breaking them down into smaller and digestible pieces. This makes it easier to see next steps, what to do and how to do it, to get it done and move on to the next thing. If you want to emulate this effect, then use your own functions to simplify.

Doing this has given me some new perspectives on myself. I realized that I am a damaged person, and that at a young age I lost the ability to feel everyday joy that drives most normal people forward. FAANG layoffs are overblown because software engineers are a profit center at those companies, most of the people fired seem to be HR types, and software engineers exist outside of tech (e.g., Walmart).
Recent layoffs are also just a reversion to mean anyway, I don't have the chart but there's a very obvious rapid hiring in the 2019/2020 area. These layoffs are just moving FAANG back into their normal employment area, so it's not like there's a recession in the tech field.
Going back to computer engineering, the field is only ~80k people and growing slowly. If anything hits that field, unemployment will spike higher than it is in CS currently. Larger job pools make frictional issues easier to deal with. In my experience CE people can usually cross skill into CS stuff pretty easily though.
